\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 $X$ and $Y$ represent random variables, with transformations such as $Z_\{1\}=X+Y$, $Z_\{2\}=X-Y$, and $Z_\{3\}=X/Y$.\u8232 \u8232 \
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 $f_X(x)$ represents the probability density function (PDF) of the random variable $X$.\u8232 
\fs22 \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 +1
\fs24 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 \
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 $F_X(x)$ represents the cumulative distribution function (CDF).\u8232 \u8232 \
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b Assumption:
\f1\b0  The PDF of $X$, denoted as $f_X(x)$, is known a priori.\uc0\u8232 
\fs22 \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 +1
\fs24 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 \
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 $y=g(x)$ denotes a new transformed random variable.\u8232 \u8232 \
\ls3\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u8232 $f_Y(y)$ and $F_Y(y)$ are used to denote the PDF and CDF of the new random variable.\u8232 
